Areva, Bollore, Ipsen, Lagardere, Vinci: French Stock Preview

-- B y   J a m e s   H e r t l i n g   a n d   H e l e n e   F o u q u e t
-- 
2011-05-03T04:01:00Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-02/areva-bollore-ipsen-lagardere-vinci-french-stock-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
whose stocks may have unusual changes in Paris. Symbols are in
parentheses after company names and prices are from the last
close.  France ’s CAC 40 Index rose 1.85, or 0.1 percent, to
4,108.77 in Paris. The SBF 120 Index rose 0.1 percent to
3,082.03.  Areva SA (CEI)  : The world’s largest maker of nuclear
reactors said first-quarter revenue rose 2.2 percent to 1.98
billion euros ($2.94 billion). The shares fell 0.1 percent to
31.09 euros.  Bollore (BOL)  SA: The holding company said first-quarter
revenue rose 27 percent to 2.05 billion euros. Shares were
unchanged at 169.80 euros.  Financiere de l’Odet (ODET)  : The holding company said
first-quarter revenue rose to 2.05 billion euros from 1.61
billion euros. Shares rose 0.1 percent to 368.78 euros.  GDF Suez (GSZ)  SA: The operator of  Europe ’s largest
natural-gas distribution grid, which operates 13 hydroelectric
plants in  Brazil , said it declined to participate in the
country’s Belo Monte dam project because the venture’s risks
outweighed the potential returns. The shares advanced 0.4
percent to 27.73 euros.  GFI Informatique (GFI)  : The consulting company said
first-quarter revenue rose to 171 million euros from 168 million
euros. Shares rose 5.7 percent to 4.07 euros.  Groupe Steria SCA (RIA)  : The computer-services company
said first-quarter revenue rose 3.5 percent to 429.1 million
euros. The shares added 1.9 percent to 22.83 euros.  Ipsen SA (IPN)  : The company reports first-quarter sales
before trading opens. Shares rose 0.2 percent to 26.50 euros.  Lagardere SCA (MMB)  : France’s largest publisher reports
first-quarter sales before trading begins. The shares rose 0.2
percent to 29.70 euros.  Vinci SA (DG)  : Chief Executive Officer Xavier Huillard
told shareholders that net profit and earnings per share will
rise “in line” with revenue growth in 2011. Vinci sales will
rise by at least 5 percent this year, he said. Shares fell 0.5
percent to 44.87 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
James Hertling in Paris at 
